146
00:06:36,919 --> 00:06:38,800
Ted Canguy asks:

147
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:41,080
“Will hyperinflation happen in China

148
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:43,499
due to over-spending in construction?

149
00:06:43,499 --> 00:06:44,900
Will China become like Venezuela

150
00:06:44,900 --> 00:06:47,780
where people are starving and can't afford
food?”

151
00:06:47,780 --> 00:06:49,699
Good question, Ted.

152
00:06:49,699 --> 00:06:53,310
It’s possible hyperinflation could happen
in China,

153
00:06:53,310 --> 00:06:55,770
but it’s not likely to happen just because
of

154
00:06:55,770 --> 00:06:58,599
overspending in construction.

155
00:06:58,599 --> 00:07:00,949
Hyperinflation is where prices rise so quickly,

156
00:07:00,949 --> 00:07:05,340
that the cost of everyday items grows literally
every day.

157
00:07:05,340 --> 00:07:08,080
In Venezuela, prices have risen so fast

158
00:07:08,080 --> 00:07:09,939
that stores started weighing money

159
00:07:09,939 --> 00:07:12,569
instead of wasting time counting it.

160
00:07:12,569 --> 00:07:14,240
To simplify things a lot,

161
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:17,720
hyperinflation tends to happen when consumers
and businesses

162
00:07:17,720 --> 00:07:20,339
massively lose confidence in the currency,

163
00:07:20,339 --> 00:07:22,289
and then the government is forced to print
extra money

164
00:07:22,289 --> 00:07:25,960
to cover expenses, which just causes more
inflation.

165
00:07:25,960 --> 00:07:27,220
In China, however,

166
00:07:27,220 --> 00:07:30,149
the government has massive foreign currency
reserves,

167
00:07:30,149 --> 00:07:32,999
including 3 trillion worth of US dollars.

168
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,580
Foreign reserves can help China stabilize
its currency.

169
00:07:36,580 --> 00:07:39,300
Not to say that China doesn’t have economic
problems

170
00:07:39,300 --> 00:07:40,640
—caused, for example,

171
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:42,460
by building too many bridges,

172
00:07:42,460 --> 00:07:45,800
or too many apartments that average workers
can’t afford.

173
00:07:45,800 --> 00:07:48,680
Or problems resulting by US trade tariffs

174
00:07:48,680 --> 00:07:50,820
that hurt Chinese manufacturing.

175
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:52,040
That being said,

176
00:07:52,050 --> 00:07:54,300
China’s economic problems won’t necessarily

177
00:07:54,300 --> 00:07:56,270
lead to hyperinflation.

178
00:07:56,270 --> 00:07:57,349
It’s possible,

179
00:07:57,349 --> 00:07:59,289
but not that likely.

180
00:07:59,289 --> 00:08:00,860
The problems might just cause people

181
00:08:00,860 --> 00:08:03,660
to lose confidence in the ruling regime.

182
00:08:03,660 --> 00:08:05,520
